04320nam a22005295i 9780226305837DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226305837  a(DE-B1597)523240  a(OCoLC)925522706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQC787.S83b.R56 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a539.73609732231 aRiordan, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTunnel Visions :bThe Rise and Fall of the Superconducting Super Collider /cMichael Riordan, Adrienne W. Kolb, Lillian Hoddeson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b47 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter one. Origins of the Super Collider -- tChapter two. A New Frontier Outpost, 1983–88 -- tChapter three. Selling the Super Collider, 1983–88 -- tChapter five. Washington and the World, 1989–92 -- tChapter six. The Demise of the SSC, 1991–94 -- tChapter seven. Reactions, Recovery, and Analysis -- tEpilogue. The Higgs Boson Discovery -- tAppendix 1. Physics at the TeV Energy Scale -- tAppendix 2 List of Interviews -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStarting in the 1950s, US physicists dominated the search for elementary particles; aided by the association of this research with national security, they held this position for decades. In an effort to maintain their hegemony and track down the elusive Higgs boson, they convinced President Reagan and Congress to support construction of the multibillion-dollar Superconducting Super Collider project in Texas—the largest basic-science project ever attempted. But after the Cold War ended and the estimated SSC cost surpassed ten billion dollars, Congress terminated the project in October 1993. Drawing on extensive archival research, contemporaneous press accounts, and over one hundred interviews with scientists, engineers, government officials, and others involved, Tunnel Visions tells the riveting story of the aborted SSC project. The authors examine the complex, interrelated causes for its demise, including problems of large-project management, continuing cost overruns, and lack of foreign contributions. In doing so, they ask whether Big Science has become too large and expensive, including whether academic scientists and their government overseers can effectively manage such an enormous undertaking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPhysicszUnited States. 0aSupercolliderszUnited States. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asuperconducting super collider, elementary particles, physics, physicists, research, science, discovery, technology, national security, higgs boson, reagan, congress, texas, cold war, large-project management, international relations, cost overruns, protons, accelerator, cern, large hadron, gigaproject, collaboration, nobel prize, nonfiction, history.1 aHoddeson, Lillian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKolb, Adrienne W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226305837423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226305837/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles